  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "FQs are categorized as highest priority critically important antimicrobials by the WHO, based on evidence of FQ resistant pathogens being transmitted to humans from non-human sources (WHO, 2024).",
    "Furthermore, FQ resistance is an interesting proof-of-concept, as both plasmid-mediated ARGs and chromosomal mutations play a role in acquired resistance.",
    "For example, FQ resistance genes such as qnrA, qnrB, qnrS and oqxAB are often located on plasmids or MGEs that are difficult to assign to a host strain using metagenomics data.",
    "Additionally, the predominant FQ resistance mechanism is based on mutations in the coding sequence of the gyrA and/or parC genes, requiring accurate SNP detection for identification (Bush et al., 2020; Kherroubi et al., 2024).",
    "Both plasmid-mediated and SNP-based FQ resistance genes are frequently detected in feces of chickens in Belgian broiler farms, making such samples ideal test cases to detect both resistance determinants in real-life conditions (Ringenier et al., under review)."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
